You'll be driven east from Ushuaia for around two hours, through a glacial valley, following the course of the Lasifashaj River, the longest river in Tierra del Fuego, to its end at the Bahía Brown on the Beagle Channel.

Here you'll have a technical and safety briefing, before embarking in a raft for a paddle in the Beagle Channel. With the expert instruction of your experienced guides, you'll paddle for about two hours to various locations for a unique view of the rugged shoreline and remote beaches.

You'll finish the rafting at the private nature reserve of Gable Island where you'll see how life was before tourism arrived in this region. A hearty lunch will be served here featuring regional food.

After lunch you'll hike south across the island to the clifftops from where you'll have a panoramic view of the Beagle Channel towards Ushuaia with Puerto Williams not far away.

After the hike you'll take a motorboat to the private nature reserve of Martillo Island where magellan and gentoo penguins arrive to nest in the summer. You'll be able to observe them from the boat, so as not to disturb their activities on the island.

Three handpicked wineries are on the agenda today, from pioneering estates dating back to the 1930s to cutting-edge organic bodegas offering biodynamic bottles.
